  planner_response {
    thinking: "**Addressing User Questions**\n\nI\'m focusing on the user\'s questions directly. The second question, about multiple agents, seems answerable through configuration of custom instructions or personas, I believe. I\'m exploring the best way to explain this in detail. I\'m moving on to address their first question about \"best use.\"\n\n\n**Clarifying Agent Capabilities**\n\nI\'m now clarifying the ability to use \"micro-agents\" or personas. The crucial point is that while only one primary agent runs at a time, users can define distinct agent profiles via `AGENTS.md` and `GEMINI.md`. These files let users dictate specific behaviors, like those of a \"Reviewer Agent\" or a \"Database Architect Agent,\" with explicit activation instructions. The main agent reads these files to embody the defined persona.\n\n\n"
    modified_response: "Yes, you can absolutely configure and customize **multiple agent personas, rules, or workflows** within me, and there is a powerful ways to get the absolute best results out of our collaboration.\n\nHere is how you can set up multiple agents, customize my behavior, and use me in the most optimal way:\n\n---\n\n### 1. Creating \"Multiple Agents\" inside me\nWhile I am the single core agent handling your workspace, you can define **different specialized agent personas** (e.g., Code Reviewer, UI/UX Designer, Database Architect, Android Specialist) that I will dynamically activate based on your requests. \n\nYou do this by creating or updating an instruction file in your project\'s root directory:\n*   **`AGENTS.md`**: Used to store custom agent profiles, persistent instructions, and specialized roles.\n*   **`gemini.md`**: Used to save project context, coding conventions, and architectural rules (as you already have a wonderfully detailed one!).\n\n#### Example setup for `AGENTS.md`:\n```markdown\n# Custom Agent Personas\n\n## \360\237\216\250 UI/UX Designer Agent\n*   **Trigger**: Whenever I ask to \"redesign\", \"improve UI\", or \"make it look modern\".\n*   **Rules**: Use Tailwind spacing, generous padding, elegant Inter/JetBrains typography, and smooth micro-animations. Avoid default gray colors; prefer warm slates.\n\n## \360\237\227\204\357\270\217 Database Architect Agent\n*   **Trigger**: When working on firestore.rules, db_setup.sql, or local Dexie storage.\n*   **Rules**: Ensure offline-first support, strict schema validations, and safe null checks to prevent app crashes.\n```\nWhenever you refer to these personas (e.g., *\"Database Architect Agent: optimizes our indexing\"*), I will immediately adopt that exact profile, ruleset, and tone.\n\n---\n\n### 2. How to use me in the best possible way\n\nTo get clean, production-ready, and bug-free code, follow these best practices:\n\n*   **Define Clear Architectural Rules**: Because I read `gemini.md` on every interaction, keeping it updated with your stack preferences (e.g., React 19, Capacitor, Dexie, Tailwind) ensures I never propose inconsistent code.\n*   **Break Down Large Features**: Instead of asking for a whole module in one go (like *\"Build a complete accounting and manufacturing system\"*), ask for specific iterative chunks (e.g., *\"Step 1: Build the UI fields for the manufacturing formulas\"* -> *\"Step 2: Connect it to Dexie/Firebase\"*). This ensures higher precision and avoids hitting token limits.\n*   **Write Real Integrations**: I can handle real APIs, Firebase configurations, OAuth flows, and build systems. Tell me your real integration intent instead of working with mock data whenever possible.\n*   **Leverage my Verification Tools**: I have built-in compilation and linting checks (`compile_applet` and `lint_applet`) to ensure whatever I write compiles successfully before completing my turn.\n\n***\n\n**Would you like me to create an `AGENTS.md` file for you now to define some custom specialized roles (e.g., a \"Capacitor Mobile Expert\" or an \"Offline Accounting Auditor\")?** Let me know what specific styles or personas you\'d like to set up!"
    thinking_duration {
      seconds: 1
      nanos: 807358378
    }
    stop_reason: STOP_REASON_STOP_PATTERN
  }
